The fix:

```
private Node tryFoldArrayAccess(Node n, Node left, Node right) {
    Node parent = n.getParent();
    // If GETPROP/GETELEM is used as assignment target the array literal is
    // acting as a temporary we can't fold it here:
    //    "[][0] += 1"
    if (parent != null && NodeUtil.isAssignmentOp(parent) && parent.getFirstChild() == n) {
      return n;
    }

    if (right.getType() != Token.NUMBER) {
      return n;
    }

    double index = right.getDouble();
    int intIndex = (int) index;
    if (intIndex != index) {
      error(INVALID_GETELEM_INDEX_ERROR, right);
      return n;
    }

    if (intIndex < 0) {
      error(INDEX_OUT_OF_BOUNDS_ERROR, right);
      return n;
    }

    Node elem = left.getFirstChild();
    for (int i = 0; elem != null && i < intIndex; i++) {
      elem = elem.getNext();
    }

    if (elem == null) {
      error(INDEX_OUT_OF_BOUNDS_ERROR, right);
      return n;
    }

    if (elem.getType() == Token.EMPTY) {
      elem = NodeUtil.newUndefinedNode(elem);
    } else {
      // Do NOT remove the element from the array literal; we are only
      // extracting its value.
    }

    // Replace the entire GETELEM with the value
    n.getParent().replaceChild(n, elem);
    reportCodeChange();
    return elem;
  }
```

But also note: we should not remove the child. So we can just delete the else branch entirely. That fixes the bug of removing child, but it's not strictly necessary for the test. However, the removal of child is a bug that could cause issues in multi-access. So minimal fix is to add the assignment check and remove the removal. To be safe, we should remove the `else` block that removes the child.

